.Cut
  that allows you to up a line
  we need to use option for cut command otherwise if we run "cut filename" it will gives us error
  -if you want to get every first letter for each line;
    calvin@localhost:~$ cut -c1 filename
  -if you want to specify which characters you want you can use numbers;
    calvin@localhost:~$ cut -c1,3,5,7 filename
  -if you want to list then range of characters
    calvin@localhost:~$ cut -c1-3 filename
  - if you want to do a specific range of characters
    calvin@localhost:~$ cut -c1-3, 6-8 filename
  -list by its size
    calvin@localhost:~$ cut -b1-3 filename
  -list first 6th column seperated by :
    calvin@localhost:~$ cut -d: -f 6 /etc/passwd


.awk
  designed for data extraxtion. Most of the time it is used to extract fields from a file or from an output
  -imagine inside a file there are 100 line and in each line there is a name and surname, so to get only name for each line;
    calvin@localhost:~$ awk '{print $1}' filename
  -for second column like for surname 
    calvin@localhost:~$ awk '{print $2}' filename
  -if i want to list what i have and i want to see the first and the third column
    calvin@localhost:~$ ls -l | awk '{print $1, $3}'
  -if you want to get the last coulmn
    calvin@localhost:~$ ls -l | awk '{print $NF}'
  -if you want to search for a specific word
    calvin@localhost:~$ awk '/jerry/ {print}' filename
  -if you wnt to output only 1st field of /etc/passwd
    calvin@localhost:~$ awk -F: '{print $1}' /etc/passwd

.grep
  to grep command which stand for global regular expressin print
  -search for a keyword from a file, like give me only the matches line, if a line include my keyword it will be displayed
    calvin@localhost:~$ grep keyword file
  -search for a keyword in a file and count
    calvin@localhost:~$ grep -c keyword file
  -search for a keyword ignore case-sensetive
    calvin@localhost:~$ grep -i kEyWord file
  -display the matched lines and their line numbers
    calvin@localhost:~$ grep -n keyword file
  -display everything but ketword, like give me everything except the keyword
    calvin@localhost:~$ grep -v keyword file

.egrep
  -search for 2 keywords
    calvin@localhost:~$ grep -i "keyword1|keyword2" file
